areaDesc.14: Strong Catholic influence in this area. Advance in rentals must be predicated on reconstructing.

areaDesc.3: Fairly new residential area surrounded by good sections. Good transportation.
areaDesc.4: Dust from coal mine. Undermining of ground. No sewers on southern hills edge
areaDesc.14: Coal operations have stayed development of this section.

15.1: W.S. Klemons - Property Appraiser, HOLC Pittsburgh

areaDesc.2: Hilly - sloping down from Brownesville Road section
areaDesc.3: Nominal
areaDesc.4: Many unpaved streets. Topography is not readily applicable to residential building. Section is very spotty with much cheap construction of considerable age.
areaDesc.14: Mortgage funds are available at 40-50% of appraisal. A good portion of these properties are built on the hillside and valley bottoms. Negro concentrated in St. Clair. Section is very spotty throughout. Many houses need paint and minor repairs.

areaDesc.3: Good transportation - near employment. Good elevation
areaDesc.4: Heavy obsolescence - houses too close together
areaDesc.14: Thrifty class of people in this locality - many old German families. Homes in the Buell foundation section are definitely better than the rest of the section; Greida St. south of Virginia.

areaDesc.3: Homogeneous development of good character. Good transportation. Very desirable residential section.
areaDesc.4: Some danger of mine cave causing houses to sag, particularly on the hill sides.
areaDesc.14: Recent letting of contract to pave Banksbille Road will add another outlet for heavy traffic into this area. The foreclosures were very heavy throughout Mt. Lebanon. About 80 % of the homes were mortgaged in 1934.

areaDesc.3: Near center of town - Near Civic Center Park
areaDesc.4: Concentration of negro and undesirables. Very congested
areaDesc.14: Considerable Jewish throughout the 5th Ave. section. Demolition for tax purposes and poor condition. Values of residential structures is expected to continue down. Rentals have about reached a peak now. North east corner is the best of the entire section: North of Webster and East of Morgan. The poorest area in the entire city. Territory bounded by 5th avenue, Congress Street, Bedford + Erin Streets. Has been mentioned for slum clearance ~which is particularly bad~.

areaDesc.3: Good transportation. Very convenient location. Good class of populace.
areaDesc.4: Age of many properties. Possibility of apartment house encroachment.
areaDesc.14: A rather old section but it is well established. About 55% of the owner-occupied homes are mortgaged. A fair second grade section. Hastings Avenue as far south as Rockshale Road has poorer housing in only fair condition.

areaDesc.3: Considered a desirable section. A wooded section of good character - good populace.
areaDesc.4: Poor transportation - isolated
areaDesc.14: Older houses not ___ during a ____ market, but new homes are being built for specific individuals. Only about 200 houses in this section. Section east of Park Road is not up to the standard of the ~rest~ balance of Rosslyn Farms area.

areaDesc.2: Hilly - rolling down from hill top
areaDesc.3: Good transportation - desirable residential section ~~
areaDesc.4: Nominal - except somewhat spotty
areaDesc.14: Crafton has larger ground units and the section is spotty. Many original owners still in the section, but younger generation is not buying locally.  Properties on hill tops are generally considered more desirable than than those on hillside; This is a fair second grade area

areaDesc.3: Good transportation - near employment area
areaDesc.4: Obsolescence setting in parts of the area. Slowly going foreign.
areaDesc.14: Loreny Ave to Charter Ave are business. Strakle Place houses are good and fairly new ranging in price up to 9,000. Ordinary section of resident home.

areaDesc.3: Near employment of well diversified character.
areaDesc.4: Subject to flood - poor housing
areaDesc.14: Little demand for housing since the 1936 flood - Values are not expected to improve from the present low level. Rents have increased as rapidly as other section because of uncertainty of receivership (?) of Preseed Steel Car Co.

areaDesc.2: Hilly - in a valley between hills
areaDesc.3: Near employment - fairly desirable residential area for better paid local workers
areaDesc.4: Mixture of older homes in fair condition
areaDesc.14: Outside city limits of McKees Rocks. Good demand for units from workers locally. RR shops - many industries located nearby.

areaDesc.2: Lies in bottom of valley - sloping up from river.
areaDesc.3: Good transportation - near employment
areaDesc.4: Old properties in poor condition - concentration of negro and foreign.
areaDesc.14: Demolition in the section - developing into light ____. Main St. is commercial. Many slum houses need held for income purposes. Other houses are not expected to increase over present valuations. Most of the dwelling units are overcrowded.
